[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:differential-privacy/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Another way to describe differential privacy is as a constraint on the algorithms used to publish aggregate information about a statistical database which limits the disclosure of private information of records in the database.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Roughly, an algorithm is differentially private if an observer seeing its output cannot tell whether a particular individual's information was used in the computation.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Differential privacy is often discussed in the context of identifying individuals whose information may be in a database.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Although it does not directly refer to identification and reidentification attacks, differentially private algorithms provably resist such attacks.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The 2006 Cynthia Dwork, Frank McSherry, Kobbi Nissim, and Adam D.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Smith article introduced the concept of ε-differential privacy, a mathematical definition for the privacy loss associated with any data release drawn from a statistical database.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The definition of ε-differential privacy requires that a change to one entry in a database only creates a small change in the probability distribution of the outputs of measurements, as seen by the attacker.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The intuition for the definition of ε-differential privacy is that a person's privacy cannot be compromised by a statistical release if their data are not in the database.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In differential privacy, each individual is given roughly the same privacy that would result from having their data removed.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] That is, the statistical functions run on the database should not be substantially affected by the removal, addition, or change of any individual in the data.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] How much any individual contributes to the result of a database query depends in part on how many people's data are involved in the query.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If the database contains data from a single person, that person's data contributes 100%.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If the database contains data from a hundred people, each person's data contributes just 1%.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The key insight of differential privacy is that as the query is made on the data of fewer and fewer people, more noise needs to be added to the query result to produce the same amount of privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Let ε be a positive real number and ${\mathcal {A}}$ be a randomized algorithm that takes a dataset as input (representing the actions of the trusted party holding the data).
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Let ${\textrm {im}}\ {\mathcal {A}}$ denote the image of ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] where the probability is taken over the randomness used by the algorithm.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This definition is sometimes called "approximate differential privacy", with "pure differential privacy" being a special case when $\delta =0$ .
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In the latter case, the algorithm is commonly said to satisfy ε-differential privacy (i.e., omitting $\delta =0$ ).
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Differential privacy offers strong and robust guarantees that facilitate modular design and analysis of differentially private mechanisms due to its composability, robustness to post-processing, and graceful degradation in the presence of correlated data.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] According to this definition, differential privacy is a condition on the release mechanism (i.e., the trusted party releasing information *about* the dataset) and not on the dataset itself.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Intuitively, this means that for any two datasets that are similar, a given differentially private algorithm will behave approximately the same on both datasets.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The definition gives a strong guarantee that presence or absence of an individual will not affect the final output of the algorithm significantly.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] For example, assume we have a database of medical records $D_{1}$ where each record is a pair (**Name**, **X**), where X is a Boolean denoting whether a person has diabetes or not.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Now suppose a malicious user (often termed an *adversary*) wants to find whether Chandler has diabetes or not.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Suppose he also knows in which row of the database Chandler resides.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Now suppose the adversary is only allowed to use a particular form of query $Q_{i}$ that returns the partial sum of the first i rows of column X in the database.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In order to find Chandler's diabetes status the adversary executes $Q_{5}(D_{1})$ and $Q_{4}(D_{1})$ , then computes their difference.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This indicates that the "Has Diabetes" field in Chandler's row must be 1.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This example highlights how individual information can be compromised even without explicitly querying for the information of a specific individual.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Continuing this example, if we construct $D_{2}$ by replacing (Chandler, 1) with (Chandler, 0) then this malicious adversary will be able to distinguish $D_{2}$ from $D_{1}$ by computing $Q_{5}-Q_{4}$ for each dataset.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If the adversary were required to receive the values $Q_{i}$ via an $\varepsilon$ -differentially private algorithm, for a sufficiently small $\varepsilon$ , then he or she would be unable to distinguish between the two datasets.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Composability refers to the fact that the joint distribution of the outputs of (possibly adaptively chosen) differentially private mechanisms satisfies differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The other important property for modular use of differential privacy is robustness to post processing.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This is defined to mean that for any deterministic or randomized function F defined over the image of the mechanism ${\mathcal {A}}$ , if ${\mathcal {A}}$ satisfies ε-differential privacy, so does $F({\mathcal {A}})$ .
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The property of composition permits modular construction and analysis of differentially private mechanisms and motivates the concept of the *privacy loss budget*.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If all elements that access sensitive data of a complex mechanisms are separately differentially private, so will be their combination, followed by arbitrary post-processing.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In general, ε-differential privacy is designed to protect the privacy between neighboring databases which differ only in one row.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This means that no adversary with arbitrary auxiliary information can know if **one** particular participant submitted their information.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] We may want to protect databases differing in c rows, which amounts to an adversary with arbitrary auxiliary information knowing if **c** particular participants submitted their information.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In other words, instead of having each item ε-differentially private protected, now every group of c items is ε-differentially private protected (and each item is $(\varepsilon /c)$ -differentially private protected).
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] One can think of differential privacy as bounding the error rates in a hypothesis test.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Since differential privacy is a probabilistic concept, any differentially private mechanism is necessarily randomized.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Some of these, like the Laplace mechanism, described below, rely on adding controlled noise to the function that we want to compute.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Others, like the exponential mechanism and posterior sampling sample from a problem-dependent family of distributions instead.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] An important definition with respect to ε-differentially private mechanisms is sensitivity.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Let d be a positive integer, ${\mathcal {D}}$ be a collection of datasets, and $f\colon {\mathcal {D}}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ be a function.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In the example of the medical database below, if we consider f to be the function $Q_{i}$ , then the sensitivity of the function is one, since changing any one of the entries in the database causes the output of the function to change by either zero or one.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This can be generalized to other metric spaces (measures of distance), and must be to make certain differentially private algorithms work, including adding noise from the Gaussian distribution (which requires the L2 norm) instead of the Laplace distribution.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] There are techniques (which are described below) using which we can create a differentially private algorithm for functions, with parameters that vary depending on their sensitivity.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The Laplace mechanism adds Laplace noise (i.e. noise from the Laplace distribution, which can be expressed by probability density function ${\text{noise}}(y)\propto \exp(-|y|/\lambda )\,\!$ , which has mean zero and standard deviation ${\sqrt {2}}\lambda \,\!$ ).
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] We can consider ${\frac {\Delta (f)}{\lambda }}\,\!$ to be the privacy factor $\varepsilon \,\!$ .
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Thus ${\mathcal {T}}\,\!$ follows a differentially private mechanism (as can be seen from the definition above).
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If we try to use this concept in our diabetes example then it follows from the above derived fact that in order to have ${\mathcal {A}}\,\!$ as the $\varepsilon \,\!$ -differential private algorithm we need to have $\lambda =1/\varepsilon \,\!$ .
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Though we have used Laplace noise here, other forms of noise, such as the Gaussian Noise, can be employed, but they may require a slight relaxation of the definition of differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If heads, then toss the coin again (ignoring the outcome), and answer the question honestly.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If tails, then toss the coin again and answer "Yes" if heads, "No" if tails.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] (The seemingly redundant extra toss in the first case is needed in situations where just the *act* of tossing a coin may be observed by others, even if the actual result stays hidden.) The confidentiality then arises from the refutability of the individual responses.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] But, overall, these data with many responses are significant, since positive responses are given to a quarter by people who do not have the *attribute A* and three-quarters by people who actually possess it.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Thus, if *p* is the true proportion of people with *A*, then we expect to obtain (1/4)(1-*p*) + (3/4)*p* = (1/4) + *p*/2 positive responses.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In particular, if the *attribute A* is synonymous with illegal behavior, then answering "Yes" is not incriminating, insofar as the person has a probability of a "Yes" response, whatever it may be.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] A transformation T is c -stable if the Hamming distance between $T(A)$ and $T(B)$ is at most c -times the Hamming distance between A and B for any two databases $A,B$ .
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] If there is a mechanism M that is $\varepsilon$ -differentially private, then the composite mechanism $M\circ T$ is $(\varepsilon \times c)$ -differentially private.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This could be generalized to group privacy, as the group size could be thought of as the Hamming distance h between A and B (where A contains the group and B does not).
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In this case $M\circ T$ is $(\varepsilon \times c\times h)$ -differentially private.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In 1977, Tore Dalenius formalized the mathematics of cell suppression.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Tore Dalenius was a Swedish statistician who contributed to statistical privacy through his 1977 paper that revealed a key point about statistical databases, which was that databases should not reveal information about an individual that is not otherwise accessible.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] He also defined a typology for statistical disclosures.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Schwartz formalized the concept of a Tracker, an adversary that could learn the confidential contents of a statistical database by creating a series of targeted queries and remembering the results.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This and future research showed that privacy properties in a database could only be preserved by considering each new query in light of (possibly all) previous queries.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This line of work is sometimes called *query privacy,* with the final result being that tracking the impact of a query on the privacy of individuals in the database was NP-hard.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] The general phenomenon is known as the Fundamental Law of Information Recovery, and its key insight, namely that in the most general case, privacy cannot be protected without injecting some amount of noise, led to development of differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] In 2006, Cynthia Dwork, Frank McSherry, Kobbi Nissim and Adam D.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Smith published an article formalizing the amount of noise that needed to be added and proposing a generalized mechanism for doing so.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] This paper also created the first formal definition of differential privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Their work was a co-recipient of the 2016 TCC Test-of-Time Award and the 2017 Gödel Prize.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Since then, subsequent research has shown that there are many ways to produce very accurate statistics from the database while still ensuring high levels of privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/differential-privacy] Because differential privacy techniques are implemented on real computers, they are vulnerable to various attacks not possible to compensate for solely in the mathematics of the techniques themselves.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Various types of personal information often come under privacy concerns.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Privacy concerns exist wherever personally identifiable information or other sensitive information is collected, stored, used, and finally destroyed or deleted – in digital form or otherwise.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Improper or non-existent disclosure control can be the root cause for privacy issues.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Informed consent mechanisms including privacy policies and dynamic consent are important in communicating to data subjects the different uses of their personally identifiable information.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Warren II and Louis Brandeis published "The Right to Privacy", an article explaining "the right to be let alone," which helped establish a right to privacy in the United States.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Their guidelines set the foundation for how privacy can be understood in terms of personal data, and influenced the development of the privacy laws of the United States.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In the United States, the Privacy Act of 1974 represented an achievement in information privacy law.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The law set a Code of Fair Information Practice to govern how federal agencies collect personal information and data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] After the Watergate and COINTELPRO scandals involving illegal government use of surveillance, this privacy law was intended to help restore public trust in the government.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Act allowed a person to have the right to access information about themselves and know how their information would be used.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The growth of the internet's popularity in the early 2000s presented different privacy concerns as many companies and organizations began to collect user's personal data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Scholars such as Daniel Solove explained the importance of informed consent.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In 2018, the Facebook–Cambridge Analytica data scandal introduced new privacy risks to the public.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] A consulting firm called Cambridge Analytica collected personal user data from over 85 million Facebook users without informed consent.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The data collected was used to assist in politically targeted ads during the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] This resulted in the United States Federal Trade Commission fining Facebook $5 billion.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Cambridge Analytica scandal influenced new legislation such as the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Information about a person's financial transactions, including the amount of assets, positions held in stocks or funds, outstanding debts, and purchases can be sensitive.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] If criminals gain access to information such as a person's accounts or credit card numbers, that person could become the victim of fraud or identity theft.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Information about a person's purchases can reveal a great deal about that person's history, such as places they have visited, whom they have contact with, products they have used, their activities and habits, or medications they have used.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In some cases, corporations may use this information to target individuals with marketing customized towards those individual's personal preferences, which that person may or may not approve.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The ability to control the information one reveals about oneself over the internet and who can access that information has become a growing concern.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] These concerns include whether email can be stored or read by third parties without consent or whether third parties can continue to track the websites that someone visited.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Another concern is whether websites one visits can collect, store, and possibly share personally identifiable information about users.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The advent of various search engines and the use of data mining created a capability for data about individuals to be collected and combined from a wide variety of sources very easily.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] AI facilitated creating inferential information about individuals and groups based on such enormous amounts of collected data, transforming the information economy.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The FTC has provided a set of guidelines that represent widely accepted concepts concerning fair information practices in an electronic marketplace, called the Fair Information Practice Principles.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] But these have been critiqued for their insufficiency in the context of AI-enabled inferential information.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The same applies to any kind of traffic generated on the Internet, including web browsing, instant messaging, and others.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In order not to give away too much personal information, emails can be encrypted and browsing of webpages as well as other online activities can be done anonymously via anonymizers, or by open source distributed anonymizers, so-called mix networks.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Nym and I2P are examples of well-known mix nets.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] With social media and e-commerce sites being used more frequently, there are more potential openings for stealing consumer's data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Companies can see which types of products consumers like to purchase and can use targeted ads to try to make people purchase more items thinking that this is what they will want to purchase.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] However, sometimes this type of data is used without explicit consent.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Users are unaware of all of the personal information that is collected about them.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Cookies track browsing data and location settings show where a person is based out of, and can show shops or products that are physically located near someone.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] These combined that be a big safety and privacy issue for users if their data is not being stored safely.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] With laws like the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), people's data can be protected and they asked for explicit consent before using said data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Globally, many nations are trying to implement similar clauses to protect consumers.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Email is not the only internet content with privacy concerns.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In an age where increasing amounts of information are online, social networking sites pose additional privacy challenges.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] People may be tagged in photos or have valuable information exposed about themselves either by choice or unexpectedly by others, referred to as participatory surveillance.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Data about location can also be accidentally published, for example, when someone posts a picture with a store as a background.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Caution should be exercised when posting information online.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Social networks vary in what they allow users to make private and what remains publicly accessible.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Without strong security settings in place and careful attention to what remains public, a person can be profiled by searching for and collecting disparate pieces of information, leading to cases of cyberstalking or reputation damage.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Cookies are used on websites so that users may allow the website to retrieve some information from the user's internet, but they usually do not mention what the data being retrieved is.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In 2018, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) passed a regulation that forces websites to visibly disclose to consumers their information privacy practices, referred to as cookie notices.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] This was issued to give consumers the choice of what information about their behavior they consent to letting websites track; however, its effectiveness is controversial.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Some websites may engage in deceptive practices such as placing cookie notices in places on the page that are not visible or only giving consumers notice that their information is being tracked but not allowing them to change their privacy settings.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Apps like Instagram and Facebook collect user data for a personalized app experience; however, they track user activity on other apps, which jeopardizes users' privacy and data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] By controlling how visible these cookie notices are, companies can discreetly collect data, giving them more power over consumers.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In the United Kingdom in 2012, the Education Secretary Michael Gove described the National Pupil Database as a "rich dataset" whose value could be "maximised" by making it more openly accessible, including to private companies.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] An example of a data request that Gove indicated had been rejected in the past, but might be possible under an improved version of privacy regulations, was for "analysis on sexual exploitation".
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] This describes the ability to control what information one reveals about oneself over cable television, and who can access that information.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] For example, third parties can track IP TV programs someone has watched at any given time.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Within academia, Institutional Review Boards function to assure that adequate measures are taken to ensure both the privacy and confidentiality of human subjects in research.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] When an individual or group of people steal consumer's data it is considered a breach of data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] It is a common threat to one's information privacy.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] This includes information such as names, date of birth, credit card information, and social security numbers.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] These types of data breaches can happen when companies do not have the most current or secure infrastructure to secure and encrypt data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] A small gap can open data to being leaked from outsiders.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] It should also be noted that breaches can happen from inside employees exposing information too.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Companies are investing time in teaching about suspicious activity and using multi factor authentication systems.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] On a federal level in Europe, governments are now mandating that companies report breaches in a timely manner.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In America HIPAA functions in a similar way and notifies patients when data has been exposed With types of guidelines in place, companies and countries are working to protect personal information and explain how personal data can and should be used.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Laws surrounding information privacy are important for protecting information globally.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] This includes laws that ensure data is collected with consent and is used with transparency .
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In the continent of Europe, a guideline called The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation requires everyone to ask for consent before using consumer data and to limit the amount of data companies need to take from users in general.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation has shown success, and has prompted other nations to follow suit.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] For example, the state of California and the country of Canada decided to create and implement their own version of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] California created the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA, 2020) and Canada created the PIPEDA (Government of Canada, 2021), both modeling their guidelines on The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation that puts consumer and user data and privacy right's first.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] More broadly, the U.S. collectively is still working on creating a comprehensive program that can protect data within the many sectors of jobs and companies operating out of the U.S.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] However, there are smaller guidelines and policies for each organization.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] For example, HIPAA or Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act protects medical patient data and information This is not on a national level that protects all user data from different types of companies, but in the U.S. there are organization and industry level protections created.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Artificial intelligence can be seen as a hindrance to protecting information privacy as they collect data widely.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] According to the International Association of Privacy Professionals, about 68% of consumers globally express concern about their privacy online with 57% agreeing that AI can be a threat to their data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] These concerns have intensified as generative AI tools, which learn from data scraped from the web, have become more widely adopted.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] AI privacy concerns can be linked to unregulated data collection methods, opaque algorithms, and data persistence.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Algorithmic opacity means not understanding exactly how and where AI is getting their data and sources from..
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The lack of clear visibility can make it difficult for someone to understand how their information is being found and used.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Data persistence is data existing for an extended period of time online that can also be without consent.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] As of now in the United States there are not any explicit federal laws governing AI in terms of data collection.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Laws such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and Gramm Leach Bliley Act can regulate companies but it excludes AI.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] There are state legislatures being enacted.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The state of Utah in the United States passed the Artificial Intelligence Policy Act in March of 2024.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The White House Office of Science and Technology Policy created the "Blueprint for an AI Bill of Rights" in 2022 which explained frameworks for data privacy and AI and having AI systems collect user consent prior to using their data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Many researchers have created additional frameworks to address AI and data privacy including data minimization requirements, auditing of AI, and giving users an option to opt out of data collection when using AI.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] As location tracking capabilities of mobile devices are advancing (location-based services), problems related to user privacy arise.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Location data is among the most sensitive data currently being collected.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] A list of potentially sensitive professional and personal information that could be inferred about an individual knowing only their mobility trace was published in 2009 by the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] These include the movements of a competitor sales force, attendance of a particular church or an individual's presence in a motel, or at an abortion clinic.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] A recent MIT study by de Montjoye et al. showed that four spatio-temporal points, approximate places and times, are enough to uniquely identify 95% of 1.5 million people in a mobility database.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The study further shows that these constraints hold even when the resolution of the dataset is low.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Therefore, even coarse or blurred datasets provide little anonymity to the person.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] People may not wish for their medical records to be revealed to others due to the confidentiality and sensitivity of what the information could reveal about their health.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] For example, they might be concerned that it might affect their insurance coverage or employment.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Or, it may be because they would not wish for others to know about any medical or psychological conditions or treatments that would bring embarrassment upon themselves.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Revealing medical data could also reveal other details about one's personal life.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Physicians and psychiatrists in many cultures and countries have standards for doctor–patient relationships, which include maintaining confidentiality.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In some cases, the physician–patient privilege is legally protected.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] These practices are in place to protect the dignity of patients, and to ensure that patients feel free to reveal complete and accurate information required for them to receive the correct treatment.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] To view the United States' laws on governing privacy of private health information, see HIPAA and the HITECH Act.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Australian law is the Privacy Act 1988 Australia as well as state-based health records legislation.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Children's online privacy is subject to legal protections in many ways.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In the United States, the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998 monitors the collection of personal information of children under 13 years of age The law specifically states that website operators must receive parental consent before collecting personal data of children.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998 applies to websites, apps, and all internet based devices that are geared towards children or know that they are collecting data from children under the age of thirteen.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Violating this law can result in penalties up to $43,792 per violation as it is enforced by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Additionally, there are state attorneys general that enforce this law.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Federal Trade Commission has continued to update the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act to meet the current update of emerging technology.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] There was an amendment made in 2013 that expanded the categories of personal information to include persistent identifiers, geolocation data, and any media with a child's description.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Federal Trade Commisision opened another review of the Children Online Privacy Protection Act in 2019 as well in order to monitor new technologies due to children utilizing mobile devices.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Some have noted that the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act does have its limitations.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The law at this time does not prevent children from accessing inappropriate content or lying about their age.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Moreover, there have been some doubts regarding how comprehensive the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act with educational technology.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Political privacy has been a concern since voting systems emerged in ancient times.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The secret ballot is the simplest and most widespread measure to ensure that political views are not known to anyone other than the voters themselves—it is nearly universal in modern democracy and considered to be a basic right of citizenship.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In fact, even where other rights of privacy do not exist, this type of privacy very often does.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] There are several forms of voting fraud or privacy violations possible with the use of digital voting machines.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The legal protection of the right to privacy in general – and of data privacy in particular – varies greatly around the world.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Laws and regulations related to Privacy and Data Protection are constantly changing; it is seen as important to keep abreast of any changes in the law and to continually reassess compliance with data privacy and security regulations.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Data protection laws across the globe aim to secure personal information and safeguard individual privacy in a digital era.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) sets a high benchmark, emphasizing consent, transparency, and robust accountability by imposing strict penalties.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Many countries adopt similar principles, mandating that organizations implement effective security measures, respect user rights, and notify breaches.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In regions such as North America, Asia, and Oceania, data protection frameworks vary from sector-specific regulations to comprehensive legislation.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Globally, these laws balance innovation with privacy, ensuring that personal data is appropriately accessible, managed ethically while mitigating misuse and cyber threats.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The United States Department of Commerce created the International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles certification program in response to the 1995 Directive on Data Protection (Directive 95/46/EC) of the European Commission.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Both the United States and the European Union officially state that they are committed to upholding information privacy of individuals, but the former has caused friction between the two by failing to meet the standards of the EU's stricter laws on personal data.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The negotiation of the Safe Harbor program was, in part, to address this long-running issue.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Directive 95/46/EC declares in Chapter IV Article 25 that personal data may only be transferred from the countries in the European Economic Area to countries which provide adequate privacy protection.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Historically, establishing adequacy required the creation of national laws broadly equivalent to those implemented by Directive 95/46/EU.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Although there are exceptions to this blanket prohibition – for example where the disclosure to a country outside the EEA is made with the consent of the relevant individual (Article 26(1)(a)) – they are limited in practical scope.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] As a result, Article 25 created a legal risk to organizations which transfer personal data from Europe to the United States.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The program regulates the exchange of passenger name record information between the EU and the US.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] According to the EU directive, personal data may only be transferred to third countries if that country provides an adequate level of protection.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Some exceptions to this rule are provided, for instance when the controller themself can guarantee that the recipient will comply with the data protection rules.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The European Commission has set up the "Working party on the Protection of Individuals with regard to the Processing of Personal Data," commonly known as the "Article 29 Working Party".
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Working Party gives advice about the level of protection in the European Union and third countries.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Working Party negotiated with U.S. representatives about the protection of personal data, the Safe Harbor Principles were the result.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Notwithstanding that approval, the self-assessment approach of the Safe Harbor remains controversial with a number of European privacy regulators and commentators.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Safe Harbor program addresses this issue in the following way: rather than a blanket law imposed on all organizations in the United States, a voluntary program is enforced by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] U.S. organizations which register with this program, having self-assessed their compliance with a number of standards, are "deemed adequate" for the purposes of Article 25.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Personal information can be sent to such organizations from the EEA without the sender being in breach of Article 25 or its EU national equivalents.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The Safe Harbor was approved as providing adequate protection for personal data, for the purposes of Article 25(6), by the European Commission on 26 July 2000.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Under the Safe Harbor, adoptee organizations need to carefully consider their compliance with the *onward transfer obligations*, where personal data originating in the EU is transferred to the US Safe Harbor, and then onward to a third country.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The alternative compliance approach of "binding corporate rules", recommended by many EU privacy regulators, resolves this issue.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In addition, any dispute arising in relation to the transfer of HR data to the US Safe Harbor must be heard by a panel of EU privacy regulators.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In July 2007, a new, controversial, Passenger Name Record agreement between the US and the EU was made.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] A short time afterwards, the Bush administration gave exemption for the Department of Homeland Security, for the Arrival and Departure Information System (ADIS) and for the Automated Target System from the 1974 Privacy Act.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] In February 2008, Jonathan Faull, the head of the EU's Commission of Home Affairs, complained about the US bilateral policy concerning PNR.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The US had signed in February 2008 a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with the Czech Republic in exchange of a visa waiver scheme, without concerting before with Brussels.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] The tensions between Washington and Brussels are mainly caused by a lesser level of data protection in the US, especially since foreigners do not benefit from the US Privacy Act of 1974.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] Other countries approached for bilateral MOU included the United Kingdom, Estonia, Germany and Greece.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] There are techniques to improve privacy, privacy-enhancing technologies, and privacy software tools.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] People building and updating systems can use privacy by design and privacy engineering strategies and techniques.
[src:differential-privacy/information-privacy] For example, by converting data into a non-readable format, encryption prevents unauthorized access.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Identifiers such as names are suppressed, non-identifying values are allowed to remain, and the quasi-identifiers need to be processed so that every distinct combination of quasi-identifiers designates at least *k* records.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The example table below presents a fictional, non-anonymized database consisting of the patient records for a fictitious hospital.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The *Name* column is an identifier, *Age*, *Gender*, *State of domicile*, and *Religion* are quasi-identifiers, and *Disease* is a non-identifying sensitive value.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Are they also non-identifying sensitive values, or are they quasi-identifiers?
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] There are 6 attributes and 10 records in this data.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] In this method, individual values of attributes are replaced with a broader category.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] For example, the value "19" of the attribute *Age* may be replaced by "≤ 20", the value "23" by "20 < Age ≤ 30", etc.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The next table shows the anonymized database.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] This data has 2-anonymity with respect to the attributes *Age*, *Gender* and *State of domicile*, since for any combination of these attributes found in any row of the table there are always at least 2 rows with those exact attributes.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The attributes available to an adversary are called quasi-identifiers.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Each quasi-identifier tuple occurs in at least *k* records for a dataset with *k*-anonymity.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The following example demonstrates a failing with *k*-anonymity: there may exist other data records that can be linked on the variables that are allegedly non-identifying.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] For instance, suppose an attacker is able to obtain the log from the person who was taking vital signs as part of the study and learns that Kishor was at the hospital on April 30 and is 180 cm tall.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] This information can be used to link with the "anonymized" database (which may have been published on the Internet) and learn that Kishor has a heart-related disease.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] An attacker who knows that Kishor visited the hospital on April 30 may be able to infer this simply knowing that Kishor is 180 cm height, roughly 80–82 kg, and comes from Karnataka.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The root of this problem is the core problem with *k*-anonymity: there is no way to mathematically, unambiguously determine whether an attribute is an identifier, a quasi-identifier, or a non-identifying sensitive value.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] In fact, all values are potentially identifying, depending on their prevalence in the population and on auxiliary data that the attacker may have.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Other privacy mechanisms such as differential privacy do not share this problem.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Although k-anonymity safeguards against identity revelations, it does not shield against the disclosure of specific attributes.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] This becomes problematic when attackers possess background knowledge.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Additionally, the absence of diversity in sensitive domains may result in the exposure of personal information.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] In such scenarios, opting for ℓ-Diversity might offer a more robust privacy safeguard.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Meyerson and Williams (2004) demonstrated that optimal *k*-anonymity is an NP-hard problem, however heuristic methods such as *k*-Optimize as given by Bayardo and Agrawal (2005) often yield effective results.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] A practical approximation algorithm that enables solving the *k*-anonymization problem with an approximation guarantee of $O(\log k)$ was presented by Kenig and Tassa.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] While *k*-anonymity is a relatively simple-to-implement approach for de-identifying a dataset prior to public release, it is susceptible to many attacks.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] When background knowledge is available to an attacker, such attacks become even more effective.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] Because *k*-anonymization does not include any randomization, attackers can make reliable, unambiguous inferences about data sets that may harm individuals.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] For example, if the 19-year-old John from Kerala is known to be in the database above, then it can be reliably said that he has either cancer, a heart-related disease, or a viral infection.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] It has also been shown that *k*-anonymity can skew the results of a data set if it disproportionately suppresses and generalizes data points with unrepresentative characteristics.
[src:differential-privacy/k-anonymity] The suppression and generalization algorithms used to *k*-anonymize datasets can be altered, however, so that they do not have such a skewing effect.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization (or pseudonymisation, the spelling under European guidelines) is one way to comply with the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) demands for secure data storage of personal information.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data can be restored to its original state with the addition of information which allows individuals to be re-identified.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] In contrast, anonymization is intended to prevent re-identification of individuals within the dataset.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] The European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) on 9 December 2021 highlighted pseudonymization as the top technical supplementary measure for Schrems II compliance.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Less than two weeks later, the EU Commission highlighted pseudonymization as an essential element of the equivalency decision for South Korea, which is the status that was lost by the United States under the Schrems II ruling by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU).
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Protects against unauthorized re-identification via the mosaic effect by generating high entropy (uncertainty) levels by dynamically assigning different tokens at different times for various purposes.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Before the Schrems II ruling, pseudonymization was a technique used by security experts or government officials to hide personally identifiable information to maintain data structure and privacy of information.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Some common examples of sensitive information include postal code, location of individuals, names of individuals, race and gender, etc.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] After the Schrems II ruling, GDPR-compliant pseudonymization must satisfy the above-noted elements as an "outcome" versus merely a technique.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] The choice of which data fields are to be pseudonymized is partly subjective.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Less selective fields, such as birth date or postal code are often also included because they are usually available from other sources and therefore make a record easier to identify.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Pseudonymizing these less identifying fields removes most of their analytic value and is therefore normally accompanied by the introduction of new derived and less identifying forms, such as year of birth or a larger postal code region.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Data fields that are less identifying, such as date of attendance, are usually not pseudonymized.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] This is because too much statistical utility is lost in doing so, not because the data cannot be identified.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] For example, given prior knowledge of a few attendance dates it is easy to identify someone's data in a pseudonymized dataset by selecting only those people with that pattern of dates.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] This is an example of an inference attack.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] The weakness of pre-GDPR pseudonymized data to inference attacks is commonly overlooked.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] A famous example is the AOL search data scandal.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] The pseudonym allows tracking back of data to its origins, which distinguishes pseudonymization from anonymization, where all person-related data that could allow backtracking has been purged.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization is an issue in, for example, patient-related data that has to be passed on securely between clinical centers.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] The application of pseudonymization to e-health intends to preserve the patient's privacy and data confidentiality.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] It allows primary use of medical records by authorized health care providers and privacy preserving secondary use by researchers.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] In the US, HIPAA provides guidelines on how health care data must be handled and data de-identification or pseudonymization is one way to simplify HIPAA compliance.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] However, plain pseudonymization for privacy preservation often reaches its limits when genetic data are involved (see also genetic privacy).
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Due to the identifying nature of genetic data, depersonalization is often not sufficient to hide the corresponding person.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Potential solutions are the combination of pseudonymization with fragmentation and encryption.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Effective as of May 25, 2018, the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) defines pseudonymization for the very first time at the EU level in Article 4(5).
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Under Article 4(5) definitional requirements, data is pseudonymized if it cannot be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of separately kept "additional information".
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data embodies the state of the art in Data Protection by Design and by Default because it requires protection of both direct and indirect identifiers (not just direct).
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Because access to separately kept "additional information" is required for re-identification, attribution of data to a specific data subject can be limited by the controller to support lawful purposes only.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] "...implement appropriate technical and organizational measures for ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] That obligation applies to the amount of personal data collected, the extent of their processing, the period of their storage and their accessibility.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] A central core of Data Protection by Design and by Default under GDPR Article 25 is enforcement of technology controls that support appropriate uses and the ability to keep promises.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] This trust cannot be maintained using outdated approaches to data protection.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization, as newly defined under the GDPR, is a means of helping to achieve Data Protection by Design and by Default to earn and maintain trust and more effectively serve businesses, researchers, healthcare providers, and everyone who relies on the integrity of data.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] GDPR-compliant pseudonymization not only enables greater privacy-respectful use of data in the "big data" world of data sharing and combining, but it also enables data controllers and processors to reap explicit benefits under the GDPR for correctly pseudonymized data.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Article 9(2)(j) with regard to overcoming the general prohibition on processing Article 9(1) special categories of personal data.
[src:differential-privacy/pseudonymization] Under Article 20(1), data controllers using Legitimate Interest processing are not subject to the right of portability, which applies only to consent-based processing.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] SDC usually refers to 'output SDC'; ensuring that, for example, a published table or graph does not disclose confidential information about respondents.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] SDC can also describe protection methods applied to the data: for example, removing names and addresses, limiting extreme values, or swapping problematic observations.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] This is sometimes referred to as 'input SDC', but is more commonly called anonymization, de-identification, or microdata protection.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] *Statistical Disclosure Control*) typically cover input SDC and tabular data protection (but not other parts of output SDC).
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] This is because these two problems are of direct interest to statistical agencies who supported the development of the field.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] For analytical environments, output rules developed for statistical agencies were generally used until data managers began arguing for specific output SDC for research.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Many kinds of social, economic and health research use potentially sensitive data as a basis for their research, such as survey or Census data, tax records, health records, educational information, etc.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Such information is usually given in confidence, and, in the case of administrative data, not always for the purpose of research.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Researchers are not usually interested in information about one single person or business; they are looking for trends among larger groups of people.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] However, the data they use is, in the first place, linked to individual people and businesses, and SDC ensures that these cannot be identified from published data, no matter how detailed or broad.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] It is possible that at the end of data analysis, the researcher somehow singles out one person or business through their research.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] For example, a researcher may identify the exceptionally good or bad service in a geriatric department within a hospital in a remote area, where only one hospital provides such care.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In that case, the data analysis 'discloses' the identity of the hospital, even if the dataset used for analysis was properly anonymised or de-identified.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Statistical disclosure control will identify this disclosure risk and ensure the results of the analysis are altered to protect confidentiality.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] It requires a balance between protecting confidentiality and ensuring the results of the data analysis are still useful for statistical research.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Output SDC relies upon having a set of rules that can be followed by an output checker; for example, that a frequency table must have a minimum number of observations, or that survival tables should be right-censored for extreme values.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The value and drawbacks of rules for frequency and magnitude tables have been discussed extensively since the late 20th Century.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] However, with awareness of the increasing need for rules for other types of analyses, a more structured approach is needed.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Some statistical outputs, such as frequency tables, have a high level of inherent risk: differencing, low numbers, class disclosure.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They therefore need to be checked before release, ideally by someone with some understanding of the data, to ensure that there is no meaningful risk on release.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] These are referred to as 'unsafe statistics'.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] However, there are some statistics, such as the coefficients from modelling, that have no meaningful risk and therefore can be released with no further checks.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] By separating statistics into 'safe' and 'unsafe', output checks can be concentrated on the latter, improving both security and efficiency.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] This is less important for official statistics, where 'unsafe' statistics such as counts, means, medians and simple indexes dominate the outputs.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] However, for research output this is important, as a great deal of research output (particularly estimates and test statistics) is inherently 'safe'.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The safe/unsafe model is useful but limited with two simple categories; within those categories, guidelines for SDC largely consist of long lists of statistics and how to handle them.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In 2023, the SACRO project https://dareuk.org.uk/driver-project-sacro/ undertook to review the whole field and see whether a more useful classification scheme could be introduced.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The result is the 'statistical barn' (or 'statbarn') concept.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They also cover most graph forms, where the graph can be converted into the appropriate statsbarn (for example, a pie chart is another form of frequency table).
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The SACRO manual provides guidance on what to look out for, and the rules to be followed for checking.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] A lookup table between statstistcs/graphs and statbarns is available on outputchecking.org.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] There are two main approaches to output SDC: *principles-based* and *rules-based.* In principles-based systems, disclosure control attempts to uphold a specific set of fundamental principles—for example, "no person should be identifiable in released microdata".
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Rules-based systems, in contrast, are evidenced by a specific set of rules that a person performing disclosure control follows (for example, "any frequency must be based on at least five observations"), after which the data are presumed to be safe to release.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In general, official statistics are rules-based; research environments are more likely to be principles-based.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In research environments, the choice of output-checking regime can have significant operational implications.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In rules-based SDC, a rigid set of rules is used to determine whether or not the results of data analysis can be released.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The rules are applied consistently, which makes it obvious what kinds of output are acceptable.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Rules-based systems are good for ensuring consistency across time, across data sources, and across production teams, which makes them appealing for statistical agencies.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Rules-based systems also work well for remote job serves such as microdata.no or Lissy.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] However, because the rules are inflexible, either disclosive information may still slip through, or the rules are over-restrictive and may only allow for results that are too broad for useful analysis to be published.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In practice, research environments running rules-based systems may have to bring flexibility in 'ad hoc' systems.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) uses a rules-based approach to releasing statistics and research results.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In principles-based SDC, both the researcher and the output checker are trained in SDC.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They receive a set of rules, which are rules-of-thumb rather than hard rules as in rules-based SDC.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] This means that in principle, any output may be approved or refused.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The rules-of-thumb are a starting point for the researcher.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] A researcher may request outputs which breach the 'rules of thumb' as long as (1) they are non-disclosive (2) they are important and (3) this is an exceptional request.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] It is up to the researcher to prove that any 'unsafe' outputs are non-disclosive, but the checker has the final say.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Since there are no hard rules, this requires knowledge on disclosure risks and judgment from both the researcher and the checker.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] It requires training and an understanding of statistics and data analysis, although it has been argued that this can be used to make the process more efficient than a rules-based model.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In the UK all major secure research environments in social science and public health, with the exception of Northern Ireland, are principles-based.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] This includes the UK Data Service's Secure Data Service, the Office for National Statistics' Secure Research Service, the Scottish Safe Havens, Secure Anonymized Information Linkage (SAIL) and OpenSAFELY.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Many contemporary statistical disclosure control techniques, such as generalization and cell suppression, have been shown to be vulnerable to attack by a hypothetical data intruder.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] For example, Cox showed in 2009 that Complementary cell suppression typically leads to "over-protected" solutions because of the need to suppress both primary and complementary cells, and even then can lead to the compromise of sensitive data when exact intervals are reported.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Many of the rules are arbitrary and reflect data owner's unwillingness to be different, rather than solid evidence.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] For example, Ritchie demonstrated the choice of a minimum threshold is more about an organisation's wish to be in line with others than any statistical rationale.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] A more substantive criticism is that the theoretical models used to explore control measures are not appropriate for guides for practical action.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Hafner et al. provide a practical example of how a change in perspective can generate substantially different results.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Artificial intelligence and machine learning models present different risks for output checking.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The GRAIMATTER project https://dareuk.org.uk/sprint-exemplar-project-graimatter/ provided some initial guidance and automatic tools.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] These were extended and simplified as part of the SACRO project (see below), and more guidelines for data services staff added.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The SDC-REBOOT community network https://www.jiscmail.ac.uk/cgi-bin/webadmin?A0=SDC-REBOOT is currently co-ordinating the ongoing development of the tools and guidance.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Output checking is generally labour-intensive, as it requires analysts who can understand what they are looking at and make a judgement about whether to release an output.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] There is therefore considerable interest in automated checking.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] tau-Argus and sdcTable are fully-automated open-source EoPR tools for tabular data protection (frequency and magnitude tables).
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They are designed to work with multiple tables.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Metadata needs to be set up describing the output(s), and the control parameters.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They provide the output checkers with extensive information on potential problems, including secondary disclosure across tables.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They can also carry out correction measures, from suppression and simple rounding to secondary suppression and controlled tabular rounding.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] They do not deal with non-tabular outputs.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] Because of the need to rewrite the metadata for each table, these tools are poorly suited for research use.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] However, in official statistics, where the same tables are being repeatedly generated and where secondary differencing is considered a significant problem, the investment in setting up the tools can be very cost-effective.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] SACRO (Semi-autonomous checking of research outputs) is a WPR tool, originally commissioned (ACRO) by Eurostat in 2020 as a proof-of-concept to show that a general-purpose output checking tool could be developed.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] In 2023 the UK Medical Research Council commissioned a generalised version (SACRO) which would work with multiple languages (as of 2024: Stata, R and Python) and provide a more user-friendly interface.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] SACRO directly implements the statbarns model and is principles-based; hence, it is 'semi-automatic' as it allows users to request exceptions and for output checkers to override the automated recommendations.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] All UK social science secure facilities, and most UK public health secure facilities, are planning to adopt it.
[src:differential-privacy/statistical-disclosure-control] The software is available on GitHub at https://github.com/AI-SDC, which also contains links to the original ACRO and tools for assessing AI models.
